#One Hot Encoding Top 10 categories

#Splitting the categories into separate items
business_df_expanded['categories_split'] = business_df_expanded['categories'].apply(lambda x: x.split(', ') if isinstance(x, str) else [])

#Getting the top 10 most common categories
all_categories = business_df_expanded['categories_split'].explode()  # Flatten the list of categories
top_10_categories = all_categories.value_counts().head(10).index.tolist()

#One-hot encoding the top 10 categories
for category in top_10_categories:
    business_df_expanded[category] = business_df_expanded['categories_split'].apply(lambda x: 1 if category in x else 0)

#Dropping the temporary 'categories_split' column
business_df_expanded = business_df_expanded.drop(columns=['categories_split'])

import ast
import pandas as pd

# Function to safely parse each entry in 'BusinessParking'
def safe_literal_eval(item):
    try:
        # Try to parse the item if it's a string
        if isinstance(item, str):
            return ast.literal_eval(item)
        # Return the item if it's already a dictionary
        elif isinstance(item, dict):
            return item
        # Return an empty dictionary for any other type
        return {}
    except (ValueError, SyntaxError):
        return {}

# Apply the parsing function to each element in the 'BusinessParking' column
business_df_expanded['BusinessParking'] = business_df_expanded['BusinessParking'].apply(safe_literal_eval)

# Normalize the 'BusinessParking' dictionary into separate columns
df_business_latest = pd.json_normalize(business_df_expanded['BusinessParking'])

# Combine the new dataframe with the original one (if needed)
business_df_expanded = pd.concat([business_df_expanded, df_business_latest], axis=1)

# Drop the 'BusinessParking' column if no longer needed
business_df_expanded = business_df_expanded.drop(columns=['BusinessParking'])

# Assuming your DataFrame is named business_df_encoded

# Function to identify outliers based on IQR
def detect_outliers_iqr(df):
    outliers = pd.DataFrame()
    for column in df.select_dtypes(include=['float64', 'int64']).columns:
        Q1 = df[column].quantile(0.25)
        Q3 = df[column].quantile(0.75)
        IQR = Q3 - Q1

        # Define outlier bounds
        lower_bound = Q1 - 1.5 * IQR
        upper_bound = Q3 + 1.5 * IQR

        # Identify outliers
        outlier_data = df[(df[column] < lower_bound) | (df[column] > upper_bound)]
        outlier_data['feature'] = column
        outliers = pd.concat([outliers, outlier_data])

    return outliers

# Get outliers from the entire dataset
outliers_iqr = detect_outliers_iqr(business_df_encoded)

## Handled missing values 
def cap_outliers(df, column):
    lower_bound = df[column].quantile(0.01)
    upper_bound = df[column].quantile(0.99)
    df[column] = np.where(df[column] < lower_bound, lower_bound, df[column])
    df[column] = np.where(df[column] > upper_bound, upper_bound, df[column])

def count_outliers(df, column):
    lower_bound = df[column].quantile(0.01)
    upper_bound = df[column].quantile(0.99)
    outliers = df[(df[column] < lower_bound) | (df[column] > upper_bound)]
    return outliers.shape[0]

def drop_outliers(df, column):
    # Calculate the lower and upper bounds
    lower_bound = df[column].quantile(0.01)
    upper_bound = df[column].quantile(0.99)
    # Drop rows where the values are outside the bounds
    df_filtered = df[(df[column] >= lower_bound) & (df[column] <= upper_bound)]
    return df_filtered

# List of columns to drop outliers from
outlier_columns_to_drop = ['review_count', 'latitude', 'longitude']

# Initialize the DataFrame
filtered_business_df = business_df_encoded

# Apply drop_outliers function to each column with remaining outliers
for column in outlier_columns_to_drop:
    filtered_business_df = drop_outliers(filtered_business_df, column)

# Show the shape of the original and the filtered DataFrames
print(f"Original DataFrame shape: {business_df_encoded.shape}")
print(f"Filtered DataFrame shape: {filtered_business_df.shape}")

fpr, tpr, _ = roc_curve(y_test, y_test_proba_improved)
plt.plot(fpr, tpr, label=f'Improved AUC = {auc_score_improved:.4f}')
plt.xlabel('False Positive Rate')
plt.ylabel('True Positive Rate')
plt.title('ROC Curve')
plt.legend()
plt.show()

Improved AUC Score: 0.3301
  • Despite applying cross-validation, regularization, the results have not significantly improved. The low test accuracy (0.1035) and the AUC score (0.3301) suggest that the model still struggles to generalize well to the test data.
  • Inference: The primary issue here seems to be that we have only used the business data and have not yet incorporated the review dataset. This omission likely limits the models ability to capture more relevant patterns, leading to poor generalization. The review dataset likely contains valuable information that can help enhance prediction performance.
  • Next Steps: We should merge the business and review datasets and build the model using this combined data. Incorporating both datasets will provide a more comprehensive view of the factors influencing the target variable and help improve model accuracy and AUC on the test set.
